title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 99 - Thumb Trigger! Very Unique!
postcontent: This listing is for a Winchester Thumb Trigger - Model 99, which is an adaptation of the Winchester model 1902. This particular model was does not have an ordinary trigger, instead this trigger is extended towards the rear of the gun beneath the firing pin. This rifle is in full working condition, and is fired by depressing the trigger on top with your thumb. It is chambered for .22LR, & .22 Short. From what I have gathered, this was the only Winchester ever made with a thumb trigger, and their first rifle listed with a rebounding lock. I am including a lot of pictures for full disclosure on condition of the rifle. If you have questions, please ask, if you want a specific picture from another angle or better lighting, please ask. This was passed down to me by my grandfather who took small game as a boy with the gun, and fortunately took very good care of it. I hope to allow someone else to enjoy it that truly appreciates the gun, that in my opinion is a very unique and interesting find for the avid collector. To view a video of the pictures of this firearm, please copy and paste the following link into a new browser - http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F_k5RQMKbbs Thanks for your interest!

title: For Sale:   Zastava M85 7.62x39 "mini mauser"
postcontent:
Selling my Zastava M85 "mini mauser" bolt action hunting rifle. This rifle is chambered in the well-known, widely available, and cost effective 7.62x39 cartridge, making it both extremely versatile and cheap to shoot. I have owned this rifle for about a year or so, bought it brand new. Took it with me down south to hunt feral hogs and here in the NE to hunt whitetail, coyotes, and ground hogs. It's essentially a 30/30 round out of a bolt action rifle, at a fraction of the cost to shoot. Great for someone who already has a 7.62x39 firearm (AK, SKS, etc.) that doesn't want to add a new caliber to their collection. 

Both the bluing and stock on this rifle are deep and rich in color. The Monte Carlo all wood stock is absolutely gorgeous. Overall this piece is in exceptional condition, can hardly tell it has been used. Accuracy is outstanding, have personally taken out 2 deer at around 200 yards and coyote/ground hogs at between 100-200 yards. I haven't had to opportunity to see what it can do past 200-250 yards, but according to the owners manual and various YouTube videos, 400-500 yards with decent ammo is well within its effective range.

Included in this package:

- Zastava M85 rifle ($525)
- Vortex Crossfire 2 (2-7x32). Great optic, zeroed at 100 yards ($150)
- Burris signature 1" Zee scope rings (medium) w/ "floating" self-centering inserts. ($50)
- bi-pod (pivots, and each leg is individually fully adjustable) ($65)
- neoprene gel sling (very comfortable and durable) ($35)
- soft rifle case that fits this rifle, along with the bi-pod and scope ($30)
- 50 rounds of high end Hornady SST (polymer tipped hunting ammo) ($45)
- 100 rounds of Wolf brand ammo (either soft point or hollow point) ($30)

Comes with owners/operating manual for the rifle and the retail box for the scope (including users manual and warranty info). 

I have over $900 invested in this package. Obviously, I want to be realistic and therefore I understand I'm not going to get that out of it. However, I think $550 is extremely fair for everything here, and the condition it is in. 

FTF only, no shipping. Must be at least 18 yrs old with a valid OH ID. Willing to meet in the greater Akron area. CCW and/or NRA card holders (like myself) are preferred. 

I would consider trades, however i am currently only looking for a 12 gauge tactical shotgun (remmy 870 tactical, mossberg 590 or 590a1, mossberg 930spx, etc.) Cash to even out either way if needed.

title: For Sale:  HUNGARIAN FEMARU P. Mod. 37 -- 'jhv41' WWII Nazi...w/ MATCHING MAG & HOLSTER C&R
postcontent: HUNGARIAN FEMARU P. Mod. 37 -- 'jhv41' WWII Nazi...w/ MATCHING MAG & HOLSTER C&R. Here's a Hungarian made Femaru Model 37 that was manufactured for the German military during WWII. The German issued pistols differed from the standard Femaru Model 37 in that they were chambered for the 7,65mm (.32 ACP) as opposed to the .380ACP, and they had a manual thumb safety added. This pistol is in very good condition and has properly matching serial numbers on frame, slide, barrel...and even one of the magazines! Manufactured in 1941, it has the German Army test proof on the left side of the slide and left side of the barrel at the muzzle. The Eagle/WaA58 German military acceptance is marked on the left side of the trigger guard. There are NO import markings. The original military blue finish rates about 93-94% overall with some normal holster/handling wear. There is no rust or pitting.

title: For Sale:  HOLSTER for a Luger P-08
postcontent:
This is a WWI era Luger P-08 Holster. It is in overall good condition - I am NOT an expert on holsters so please ask me questions! I will be as detailed and thorough as possible.

I bought my Luger from a good friend about 6 years ago and the Luger came with the holster. He purchased the holster after he bought the Luger so they were not a matching set (otherwise I would keep it).

The leather is in overall good condition and shows some scuff spots but mostly a nice dark brown. The buckle is in good shape and metal shots some patina and wear, but still works. My Luger fits in it very snugly, no wiggle room or anything. The draw strap is also intact. Only markings are located on the back of the holster, and on the inside of the flap.
The back reads "L.Z.A (followed by an eagle emblem) J. Colin. On the inside of the flap there is a big black inc stamp marked "B.A.XT" and a seal that has writing in a circular pattern (sorry hard to read with my eyes and it appears German) around the date, 1917. From what I can tell the L.Z.A is a production stamp from the leather manufacturer and the B.A.XT is a military acceptance mark.

title: For Sale:   COLT MODEL 1905 .45 AUTO -- Pre-1911...Scarce Pistol, Only 6210 Made...C&R OK
postcontent: Here's a fairly scarce Colt auto-pistol! This is a Model 1905 .45 Automatic...the predecessor to the famous Colt 1911. At the time this pistol was conceived, the U.S. Army was seeking a suitable semi-automatic pistol chambered in .45 caliber. John Browning adapted the current production Model 1902 Military (a .38 Caliber automatic) to a newly designed .45 caliber automatic cartridge in a first attempt toward meeting the military requirements. Although the 1905 was not accepted by the military, it did meet with some modest success on the civilian market and 6210 were produced between 1905-1912. Further developments and the eventual adoption of the Model 1911 by the U.S. military brought production of the 1905 to an end. Like the Model 1902 military and the earlier Colt autos, the Model 1905 operates using the parallel ruler principal where the barrel is attached to the frame by swivel links at both the front and rear. A "wedge" at the front of the pistol passes through the frame and secures the slide. This pistol is in good original condition and retains a fair amount of original blue finish.
